classes.name: DbCollection
classes.description:
The collection attached to the database object.

For example if you had the following data file named mirage/fixtures/contacts.js

export default [
  {id: 1, name: 'Zelda'},
  {id: 2, name: 'Link'}
];

then db.contacts would return this array.

methods.name: all
methods.description: Returns a copy of the data, to prevent inadvertent data manipulation.

methods.name: insert
methods.description:
Inserts data into the collection. data can be a single object or an array of objects. Returns the inserted record.

// Insert a single record
let link = db.users.insert({name: 'Link', age: 173});

link;  // {id: 1, name: 'Link', age: 137}

// Insert an array
let users = db.users.insert([
  {name: 'Zelda', age: 142},
  {name: 'Epona', age: 58},
]);

users;  // [{id: 2, name: 'Zelda', age: 142}, {id: 3, name: 'Epona', age: 58}]

methods.name: find
methods.description: Returns a single record from the collection if ids is a single id, or an array of records if ids is an array of ids. Note each id can be an int or a string, but integer ids as strings (e.g. the string “1”) will be treated as integers.

methods.name: findBy
methods.description: Returns the first model from collection that matches the key-value pairs in the query object. Note that a string comparison is used. query is a POJO.

methods.name: where
methods.description: Returns an array of models from collection that match the key-value pairs in the query object. Note that a string comparison is used. query is a POJO.

methods.name: firstOrCreate
methods.description: Finds the first record matching the provided query in collection, or creates a new record using a merge of the query and optional attributesForCreate.

methods.name: update
methods.description: Updates one or more records in collection. If attrs is the only arg present, updates all records in the collection according to the key-value pairs in attrs. If target is present, restricts updates to those that match target. If target is a number or string, finds a single record whose id is target to update. If target is a POJO, queries collection for records that match the key-value pairs in target, and updates their attrs. Returns the updated record or records.

methods.name: remove
methods.description: Removes one or more records in collection. If target is undefined, removes all records. If target is a number or string, removes a single record using target as id. If target is a POJO, queries collection for records that match the key-value pairs in target, and removes them from the collection.

classes.name: Collection
classes.description:
Collections represent arrays of models. They are returned by a hasMany association, or by one of the ModelClass query methods:

let posts = user.blogPosts;
let posts = schema.blogPosts.all();
let posts = schema.blogPosts.find([1, 2, 4]);
let posts = schema.blogPosts.where({ published: true });

methods.name: update
methods.description:
Updates each model in the collection, and immediately persists all changes to the db.

let posts = author.blogPosts.all();

posts.update('published', true); // the db was updated for all posts

methods.name: destroy
methods.description:
Destroys the db record for all models in the collection.

let posts = author.blogPosts.all();

posts.destroy(); // all posts removed from db

methods.name: save
methods.description:
Saves all models in the collection.

let posts = author.blogPosts.all();

posts.models[0].published = true;

posts.save(); // all posts saved to db

methods.name: reload
methods.description: Reloads each model in the collection.

methods.name: add
methods.description:
Adds a model to this collection.

user.posts.add(newPost);

methods.name: remove
methods.description: Removes a model to this collection

methods.name: includes
methods.description: Checks if the collection includes the model

methods.name: sort
methods.description:
Returns a new Collection with its models sorted according to the provided compare function.

let posts = author.blogPosts.all();

let postsByTitleAsc = posts.sort((a, b) => {
  return b.title < a.title;
});

methods.name: toString
methods.description: Simple string representation of the collection and id.

accessors.name: length
accessors.description:
The number of models in the collection.

user.posts.length; // 2

methods.name: save
methods.description: Creates or saves the model.

methods.name: update
methods.description: Update the record in the db.

methods.name: destroy
methods.description: Destroys the db record

methods.name: isNew
methods.description:
Boolean, true if the model has not been persisted yet to the db.

Originally this method simply checked if the model had an id; however, we let people create models with pre-specified ids. So, we have to check whether the record is in the actual databse or not.

methods.name: isSaved
methods.description: Boolean, opposite of isNew

methods.name: reload
methods.description: Reload a model’s data from the database.

methods.name: associationFor
methods.description: Returns the association for the given key

methods.name: inverseFor
methods.description:
Returns this model's inverse association for the given model-type-association pair, if it exists.

Example:

post: Model.extend({
  comments: hasMany()
}),
comments: Model.extend({
  post: belongsTo()
})

post.inversefor(commentsPostAssociation) would return the post.comments association object.

Originally we had association.inverse() but that became impossible with the addition of polymorphic models. Consider the following:

post: Model.extend({
  comments: hasMany()
}),
picture: Model.extend({
  comments: hasMany()
}),
comments: Model.extend({
  commentable: belongsTo({ polymorphic: true })
})

commentable.inverse() is ambiguous - does it return post.comments or picture.comments? Instead we need to ask each model if it has an inverse for a given association. post.inverseFor(commentable) is no longer ambiguous.

params.name: modelName
params.description: The model name of the class we're scanning

methods.name: _explicitInverseFor
methods.description: Finds the inverse for an association that explicity defines it's inverse

methods.name: _checkForMultipleExplicitInverses
methods.description:
Ensures multiple explicit inverses don't exist on the current model for the given association.

TODO: move this to compile-time check

methods.name: _implicitInverseFor
methods.description: Finds if there is an inverse for an association that does not explicitly define one.

methods.name: hasInverseFor
methods.description: Returns whether this model has an inverse association for the given model-type-association pair.

methods.name: alreadyAssociatedWith
methods.description: Used to check if models match each other. If models are saved, we check model type and id, since they could have other non-persisted properties that are different.

methods.name: _setupAttrs
methods.description: model.attrs represents the persistable attributes, i.e. your db table fields.

methods.name: _definePlainAttribute
methods.description: Define getter/setter for a plain attribute

methods.name: _setupRelationships
methods.description:
Foreign keys get set on attrs directly (to avoid potential recursion), but model references use the setter.

We validate foreign keys during instantiation.

methods.name: _validateForeignKeyExistsInDatabase
methods.description: Originally we validated this via association.setId method, but it triggered recursion. That method is designed for updating an existing model's ID so this method is needed during instantiation.

methods.name: _saveAssociations
methods.description: Update associated children when saving a collection

methods.description: Simple string representation of the model and id.

methods.description: Checks the equality of this model and the passed-in model

classes.name: PolymorphicCollection
classes.description:
An array of models, returned from one of the schema query methods (all, find, where). Knows how to update and destroy its models.

Identical to Collection except it can contain a heterogeneous array of models. Thus, it has no modelName property. This lets serializers and other parts of the system interact with it differently.

methods.name: update
methods.description: Updates each model in the collection (persisting immediately to the db).

methods.name: destroy
methods.description: Destroys the db record for all models in the collection.

methods.name: save
methods.description: Saves all models in the collection.

methods.name: reload
methods.description: Reloads each model in the collection.

methods.name: add
methods.description: Adds a model to this collection

methods.name: remove
methods.description: Removes a model to this collection

methods.name: includes
methods.description: Checks if the collection includes the model

methods.name: toString
methods.description: Simple string representation of the collection and id.

accessors.name: length
accessors.description: Number of models in the collection.

methods.name: _hydrate
methods.description: Takes a record and returns a model, or an array of records and returns a collection.

methods.name: serialize
methods.description: Override this method to implement your own custom serialize function. primaryResource is whatever was returned from your route handler, and request is the Pretender request object. Returns a plain JavaScript object or array, which Mirage uses as the response data to your Ember app’s XHR request. You can also override this method, call super, and manipulate the data before Mirage responds with it. This is a great place to add metadata, or for one-off operations that don’t fit neatly into any of Mirage’s other abstractions.

methods.name: keyForModel
methods.description: Used to define a custom key when serializing a primary model of modelName modelName.

methods.name: keyForCollection
methods.description: Used to customize the key when serializing a primary collection. By default this pluralizes the return value of keyForModel.

methods.name: keyForAttribute
methods.description: Used to customize how a model’s attribute is formatted in your JSON payload.

methods.name: keyForRelationship
methods.description:
Use this hook to format the key for collections related to this model.

For example, if you're serializing an author that side loads many blogPosts, you would get blogPost as an argument, and whatever you return would end up as the collection key in your JSON:

keyForRelationship(type) { return dasherize(type); }

{ author: {...}, 'blog-posts': [...] }

methods.name: keyForRelationshipIds
methods.description:
Use this hook to format the key for relationship ids in this model's JSON representation.

For example, if you're serializing an author that side loads many blogPosts, you would get blogPost as an argument, and whatever you return would end up as part of the author JSON:

keyForRelationshipIds(type) { return dasherize(type) + '-ids'; }

{ author: { ..., 'blog-post-ids': [1, 2, 3] }, 'blog-posts': [...] }

methods.name: normalize
methods.description:
This method is used by the POST and PUT shorthands. These shorthands expect a valid JSON:API document as part of the request, so that they know how to create or update the appropriate resouce. The normalize method allows you to transform your request body into a JSON:API document, which lets you take advantage of the shorthands when you otherwise may not be able to.

Note that this method is a noop if you’re using JSON:API already, since request payloads sent along with POST and PUT requests will already be in the correct format.

classes.name: Server
classes.description:
The Mirage server.

Note that this within your config function in mirage/config.js refers to the server instance, which is the same instance that server refers to in your tests.

methods.name: config
methods.description:
Set the base namespace used for all routes defined with get, post, put or del.

For example,

// app/mirage/config.js
export default function() {

  this.namespace = '/api';

  // this route will handle the URL '/api/contacts'
  this.get('/contacts', 'contacts');
};

Note that only routes defined after this.namespace are affected. This is useful if you have a few one-off routes that you don't want under your namespace:

// app/mirage/config.js
export default function() {

  // this route handles /auth
  this.get('/auth', function() { ...});

  this.namespace = '/api';
  // this route will handle the URL '/api/contacts'
  this.get('/contacts', 'contacts');
};

If your Ember app is loaded from the filesystem vs. a server (e.g. via Cordova or Electron vs. ember s or https://yourhost.com/), you will need to explicitly define a namespace. Likely values are / (if requests are made with relative paths) or https://yourhost.com/api/... (if requests are made to a defined server).

For a sample implementation leveraging a configured API host & namespace, check out this issue comment
